rization in the United States. This book argues that lessons for addressing these national challenges are emerging from a new set of realities in America's metropolitan regions: first, that inequity is, in fact, bad for economic growth; second, that bringing together the concerns of equity and growth requires concerted local action; and, third, that the fundamental building block for doing this is the creation of diverse and dynamic epistemic (or knowledge) communities, which help to overcome political polarization and help regions address the challenges of economic restructuring and social divides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCities and townszUnited StatesxEconomic policy. 0aEconomic development projectszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 0aRegional planningzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aamerican politics.  acase studies.  acollaboration.  aconcerted local action.  aeconomic challenges.  aeconomic growth.  aeconomic restructuring.  aepistemic communities.  aincome inequality.  ainequality.  ainequity.  ametropolitan regions.  amoney.  anational challenges.  anational politics.  anew economy.  aoklahoma city.  aplanning for progress.  apolitical polarization.  apolitical.  apower and wealth.  aregression analysis.  asacramento.  asalt lake city.  asan antonio.  aseattle.  asilicon valley.  asocial divides.  aunited states of america.  aurban areas.  awealth.1 aPastor, Manuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/au